@100 = ~Cragmyr's Revenge: Sword of Sharpness~
@101 = ~This old sword has clearly seen better days, but it still holds a sharp edge. The sword has been carried by the Lords of the Cragmyr Keep for as long as anyone can remember. Its power is still great and with a good hit, it will cause severe bleeding and injury to the target's limbs.

STATISTICS:

Combat abilities:
25% chance per hit that the target must save vs. Death at -2 or suffer 2 hp/round bleeding damage and have a limb injury for next 2 rounds (movement speed penalty -5)

Equipped abilities:
+5% chance to score critical hits
This weapon is treated as +3 for purposes of who or what can be hit by it

THAC0: +1
Damage: 2d4+1 (slashing)
Speed Factor: 7
Proficiency Type: Bastard Sword
Type: One-handed
Requires:
 11 Strength

Weight: 9~



@102 = ~Iltarian Shoon Impering~
@103 = ~The Shoon Impering used to be a ring. The ring and several of its type were originally crafted by wizards of the Shoon Imperium mages to make their spell casting more quick. Many of the rings and even more powerful of its kind have somehow for unknown reasons ended up in the hands of the Cowled Wizards. This particular ring's magic and power was however transformed into a pair of ioun stones by Iltar.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
Improves casting speed by 1
Caster level increased by 1

Weight: 2~



@104 = ~Spell Diver~
@105 = ~The sellsword Naradon of Thesk was known for his ability to quickly and efficiently defeat enemy mages even when outnumbered. He earned this reputation with the help of three items: Potions of Speed, Boots of Speed, and his trusted short sword, Spell Diver. Unlike many other magical weapons, Spell Diver does not have a dark, murderous history. Naradon retired from adventuring when he was thirty-two. His fondness for Potions of Speed caught up with him when he died of old age four years later. His only heir had no desires to be an adventurer. He sold the weapon to a known cat burglar a few years after his father's death. The sword can be recognized by the kingfisher stamped into the ricasso.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
Save vs. Spell: +1

Damage: 1d6+2 (piercing)
THAC0: +2
Special: 50% of all hits nullify the target's ability cast spells for 1 round
Speed Factor: 1
Proficiency Type: Short Sword
Type: One-handed
Requires:
 4 Strength

Weight: 2~



@106 = ~Quinn's Note~
@107 = ~If I end up dead, please believe me when I write this: I am not a deserter. Me and my wife were attacked by a Flaming Fist Battle Wizard during the night. I myself suspect Horben, since Luci knew something about Officer Hjout's and Horben's discriminating dealings. I sadly do not know what she knew. I believe Horben used Trap the Soul spell to imprison Luci into a gem, and I have no way of releasing her or finding out where she might be. I guess when the heat goes away from me I should look for Harpers, monks of Candlekeep or the Cowled Wizards for help. They do have a lot of magical resources and that's what is needed to find her.~



@108 = ~Belib's Multiple Tool~
@109 = ~Belib the Wary was a very bright gnome, and self-proclaimed adventurer, who believed in covering every angle of his tiny arse before leaving on grand quests.  He created magical items that literally saturated the gamut of possible situations that could arise from his high adventures.  These magical items would have been the envy of all adventurers, had Belib been successful in leaving his domicile with his equipment.

After many years of creating his incredible inventory of enchanted do-dads, Belib finally gathered his wares into an immense backpack (naturally, it was enchanted to carry far more than what would normally fit into a gnome's pack) and set out to quest for the grandest quests.  Unfortunately for Belib, one of his tiny feet tripped over his home's threshold and he was summarily crushed under the enormous weight of his pack.  The backpack burst open and scattered his enchanted wares all across his front yard.  One would like to think that passing sentient beings would stop and help the crushed gnome, but the most that passersby did was loot Belib's goods.

One of Belib's more popular goodies, especially with the vermin that make stealing and looting a career, was Belib's Multiple Tool.  Disguised as an ornate amulet, this tool would help make even the most inept rogue a master of lock picking and trap disarming.  As is usually the case with items that aid in the thieving arts, Belib's Multiple Tool has found its way into many greased palms over the years.

STATISTICS:

Special:
+10% to Open Locks
+10% to Find Traps

Weight: 1~



